dat <- readRDS("phys_all.rds")
data("state")

EPs <- dat %>% filter(st %in% c(state.abb, "DC") & hosp_afl_1 == '') %>% 
  filter(gndr %in% c("F", "M") & !is.na(grd_yr)) %>% 
  mutate(yrs_grd = 2016 - as.integer(grd_yr),
         cred = case_when(cred == '' ~ 'NA',
                          TRUE ~ as.character(cred)),
         cred = as.factor(cred),
         ehr = case_when(ehr == 'Y' ~ 1,
                         ehr == '' ~ 0),
         ehr = as.factor(ehr)) %>% 
  select(-hosp_afl_1, -hosp_afl_lbn_1, -frst_nm) %>% 
  arrange(desc(ehr)) %>% 
  distinct(npi, .keep_all = TRUE)

# calculate the number of practices for each physician
SL <- dat %>% group_by(npi) %>% summarise(locations = n_distinct(zip))

EPs <- left_join(EPs, SL, by="npi")

summary(EPs)

in the grand scheme of things, i think its safe to say that gender is pretty independent of years since graduation. so we should be able to add them into the model together without them influencing each others effects. Also, the distribution of years since graduation is pretty skewed, we used a square root scale so thats why the kernel density curves in the violin plots look more symmetric than the histograms from ggpairs. The actual raw values of the years since graduation were not square-root transformed though so we can see and intepret the actual years rather than the square root of the years.

update: i later added in the number of locations just because its another continuous variable we can look at, but really most physicians in the data have only one practice location and then theres a jump to a few physicians who have >300 unique zip codes of all their practices. this distribution is seen equally across genders and years since graduation, so clearly very independent of the two other variables - so it can be safely added to the model. but im just afraid that this information is already not so valid? its really more of a categorical variable.

  1. credentials is one of the categorical variables with the least number of levels, lets see if we can add this into the model too. first check the relationship between years since graduation and credentials.
EPs %>% mutate(cred = reorder(cred, yrs_grd)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(cred, yrs_grd)) +
  stat_sum(aes(size = ..n.., group = 1)) +
  scale_size_area(max_size = 10)

the distribution of years since graduation looks pretty consistent across different levels of credentials, except for AA due to small sample size and NA due to disproportionally large sample size. NA is unknown credential and unfortunately the majority of our physicians fell in that category (perhaps many people skip the credentials field because its not a required field or unnecessary if the dataset is already going to be mostly doctors?) anyway, this tells us that we probably shouldnt use credentials as a variable since its mostly missing (~75% NAs).

a general observation is that there are proportionally more physicians in our data who have not used EHR. so we already have an imbalance in sample size between the two groups. but overall, our sample size is still large enough.

logistic regression model: effects of physicial-level demographics on the use of EHR

# fit the model
model <- glm(ehr ~ gndr + yrs_grd + locations, data = EPs, family = binomial)
summary(model)
